<subSubSection id="C331C195B757FFE9FD6AFA56FBF1FE91" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB757FFE9FD6AFA56FC2AF007" blockId="16.[704,1300,1517,1940]" pageId="16" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB757FFE9FD6AFA56FC97F054" bold="true" box="[705,860,1517,1546]" pageId="16" pageNumber="123">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FCC7FA56FCA9F06C" authorityName="J. A. Allen" authorityYear="1890" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Lepus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="sylvaticus" subSpecies="floridanus">Lepus sylvaticus floridanus J. A. Allen, 1890</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="3B439843B757FFE9FCD9F9A2FC2AF007" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3805018343" pageId="16" pageNumber="123">“Sebastian River, Brevard Co., Fla. [Florida],” USA.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94921EB757FFE9FD6AF9E4FBF1FE91" blockId="16.[704,1300,1517,1940]" lastBlockId="16.[94,1300,1947,3476]" pageId="16" pageNumber="123">
Taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FBA9F9E4FB64F0DE" baseAuthorityName="J. A. Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[1026,1199,1631,1664]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="floridanus">S. floridanus</taxonomicName>
needs revision. Formerly, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FC76F93CFB4CF0F6" baseAuthorityName="J. A. Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[989,1159,1671,1704]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flondanus">S. flondanus</taxonomicName>
included 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FD68F915FC82F091" baseAuthorityName="Bailey" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[707,841,1710,1743]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">S. robustus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FC25F915FBD1F091" authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1907" box="[910,1050,1710,1743]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cognatus">S. cognatus</taxonomicName>
as subspecies, but they are now recognized as distinct species. Subspecies holzneri is provisionally retained as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FC61F89FFBA4F11B" baseAuthorityName="J. A. Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[970,1135,1828,1861]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="floridanus">S. floridanus</taxonomicName>
because its relationship to Mexican populations offloridanus has not yet been reported. Genetic similarities suggest that subspecific designations are not warranted for S. floridanusin the north-eastern USA. Genetic studies on widely separated populations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FB85F879FB05F1BD" baseAuthorityName="J. A. Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[1070,1230,1986,2019]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="floridanus">S. floridanus</taxonomicName>
indicate considerably intraspecific genetic variability. As taxonomists are still trying to clarify the species differentiation in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB757FFE9FE5FF7AAFDBAFE6C" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[500,625,2065,2098]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Sylvilagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="16" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sylvilagus</taxonomicName>
, the subspecific taxonomyis still unresolved; the original descriptions of subspecies are often not very helpful as they are mostly based on a few external characters and on a small numbers of individuals. It has been shown that the variability is clinal in more careful investigations; hence, the ranges in subspecies might be arbitrary and unreasonable. Thirty-one subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
